---
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
import SiteHeader from "@/components/SiteHeader.astro";
import SiteFooter from "@/components/SiteFooter.astro";
import { GITHUB_REPO } from "@/lib/site";
---

<Layout
  title="Path A: Cloudflare Tunnel — LetsChat Self-Hosting"
  description="Deploy LetsChat using Cloudflare Tunnel for zero-trust HTTP ingress with LiveKit media via direct port forwarding."
>
  <SiteHeader active="self-hosting" />

  <main class="relative max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 py-16 space-y-10 overflow-hidden">
    <div class="hero-glow hero-glow-a"></div>

    <div class="relative z-10 space-y-2">
      <nav class="flex items-center gap-2 text-xs text-muted-foreground">
        <a href="/self-hosting" class="hover:text-foreground transition-colors">Self-Hosting</a>
        <span>/</span>
        <span class="text-foreground">Path A: Cloudflare Tunnel</span>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-semibold tracking-tight">Path A: Cloudflare Tunnel</h1>
      <p class="text-muted-foreground max-w-2xl leading-relaxed pt-1">
        Routes <code class="text-xs">auth/chat/files/connect</code> plus LiveKit <strong>signalling</strong> over Cloudflare Tunnel so your host is never directly exposed on ports 80/443, and signalling inherits Cloudflare TLS.
        LiveKit <strong>media</strong> (UDP/TCP SRTP) still requires direct port forwarding — it cannot ride the tunnel.
      </p>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 text-xs pt-2">
        <span class="mini-pill">Zero Trust Ingress</span>
        <span class="mini-pill">Lower Host Exposure</span>
        <span class="mini-pill">Cloudflare-managed domain required</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <section class="space-y-6">

      <article class="step-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-medium">Requirements (Read First)</h2>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 text-sm text-muted-foreground space-y-1">
          <li>Ubuntu host with Docker Engine + Compose plugin.</li>
          <li>Cloudflare-managed domain plus Zero Trust access (to create a tunnel token).</li>
          <li>Admin access to your router to port-forward LiveKit media (<code class="text-xs">44381/tcp+udp</code>, <code class="text-xs">44382/udp</code>) — this is a manual step, covered in Step 6.</li>
          <li>A routable public IPv4, <strong>not</strong> CGNAT. Step 6a shows how to check; CGNAT users need a TURN relay (note after Step 8).</li>
        </ul>
        <pre class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-background p-4 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`docker --version
docker compose version
curl -4 ifconfig.me`}</code></pre>
      </article>

      <article class="step-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-medium">How This Path Works</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Cloudflare Tunnel proxies HTTP/WebSocket services (<code class="text-xs">auth/chat/files/connect</code>) from Cloudflare to your Docker network.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">LiveKit signalling (the WebSocket on port 44380) is also proxied — add an <code class="text-xs">lk.example.com</code> ingress rule so it gets <code class="text-xs">wss://</code> with Cloudflare TLS.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">LiveKit media is different: raw UDP/TCP SRTP must still be reachable directly on your host via router forwarding. Clients learn the host's public IP from the ICE candidates, so media does not depend on the <code class="text-xs">lk.example.com</code> DNS record.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="step-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-medium">Step 0: Get Shared Files</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Download the shared base compose file and LiveKit config:</p>
        <pre class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-background p-4 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`mkdir letschat && cd letschat

wget https://raw.githubusercontent.com/${GITHUB_REPO}/main/docker-compose.prod.base.yml

mkdir livekit
wget -O livekit/config.prod.yaml \\
  https://raw.githubusercontent.com/${GITHUB_REPO}/main/livekit/config.prod.yaml`}</code></pre>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">All images are pre-built — no Rust or Node toolchains needed on the server.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="step-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-medium">Step 1: Download Path A Files</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Inside the <code class="text-xs">letschat</code> directory:</p>
        <pre class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-background p-4 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`wget https://raw.githubusercontent.com/${GITHUB_REPO}/main/docker-compose.prod.tunnel.yml

wget -O .env \\
  https://raw.githubusercontent.com/${GITHUB_REPO}/main/.env.production.tunnel.example`}</code></pre>
      </article>

      <article class="step-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-medium">Step 2: DNS + Tunnel Ingress</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Create these hostnames in Cloudflare Zero Trust and configure tunnel ingress rules:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 text-sm text-muted-foreground space-y-1">
          <li><code class="text-xs">auth.example.com</code> → <code class="text-xs">http://core-api:8787</code></li>
          <li><code class="text-xs">chat.example.com</code> → <code class="text-xs">http://spacetimedb:3000</code> (enable WebSocket support)</li>
          <li><code class="text-xs">files.example.com</code> → <code class="text-xs">http://minio:44390</code></li>
          <li><code class="text-xs">connect.example.com</code> → <code class="text-xs">http://core-api:8787</code></li>
          <li><code class="text-xs">lk.example.com</code> → <code class="text-xs">http://livekit:44380</code> (enable WebSocket support — this is LiveKit signalling only; media reaches the host directly via the forwarded ports)</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Copy the tunnel token from the Zero Trust dashboard — you will need it in the next step.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="step-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-medium">Step 3: Configure Secrets and Endpoints</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Open <code class="text-xs">.env</code> and replace every placeholder. Generate secrets with:</p>
        <pre class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-background p-4 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`openssl rand -hex 32      # for AUTH_JWT_SECRET, MINIO_SECRET_KEY
openssl rand -base64 32   # for LIVEKIT_API_SECRET`}</code></pre>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Key fields to fill in:</p>
        <pre class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-background p-4 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`AUTH_JWT_SECRET=          # generate with openssl
LIVEKIT_API_KEY=letschat-prod
LIVEKIT_API_SECRET=       # generate with openssl
MINIO_ACCESS_KEY=         # any username you choose
MINIO_SECRET_KEY=         # generate with openssl
MINIO_PUBLIC_ENDPOINT=https://files.example.com
DISCOVERY_SPACETIMEDB_URI=wss://chat.example.com
DISCOVERY_AUTH_URL=https://auth.example.com
DISCOVERY_LIVEKIT_URL=wss://lk.example.com
CLOUDFLARE_TUNNEL_TOKEN=  # from Zero Trust dashboard`}</code></pre>
      </article>

      <article class="step-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-medium">Step 4: Configure LiveKit</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Open <code class="text-xs">livekit/config.prod.yaml</code> and replace the key/secret placeholder so it matches your <code class="text-xs">.env</code>:</p>
        <pre class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-background p-4 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`keys:
  letschat-prod: <paste LIVEKIT_API_SECRET here>`}</code></pre>
        <p class="text-xs text-muted-foreground">The rest of the file (ports, <code class="text-xs">use_external_ip: true</code>) can stay as-is for most home server setups.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="step-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-medium">Step 5: Pull Images and Start</h2>
        <pre class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-background p-4 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.base.yml -f docker-compose.prod.tunnel.yml pull
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.base.yml -f docker-compose.prod.tunnel.yml up -d
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.base.yml -f docker-compose.prod.tunnel.yml ps`}</code></pre>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground"><code class="text-xs">module-init</code> automatically publishes the SpacetimeDB module once the database is healthy. Watch its progress with:</p>
        <pre class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-background p-4 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`docker logs letschat-module-init`}</code></pre>
      </article>

      <article class="step-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-medium">Step 6: Forward LiveKit Media Ports on Your Router</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">The tunnel carries everything <span class="italic">except</span> voice/video media. That media is raw UDP/TCP and must reach your server directly, so you forward it on your router. <strong>This is the one step the tunnel cannot do for you</strong> — skip it and text chat works fine but voice channels connect with no audio.</p>

        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground"><strong>6a. First check you are not behind CGNAT.</strong> Carrier-grade NAT (common on some fibre/cable plans, and on mobile/Starlink) makes port forwarding impossible. Compare your true public IP to your router's WAN IP:</p>
        <pre class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-background p-4 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`curl -4 ifconfig.me        # your true public IP, as seen from the internet`}</code></pre>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Open your router's status page and find its WAN / Internet IP. <strong>If they match</strong>, forwarding will work — continue. <strong>If they differ</strong>, your ISP has you behind CGNAT and no router setting will fix it; you need a TURN relay (see the note after Step 8).</p>

        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground"><strong>6b. Find the server's LAN IP</strong> and give it a static DHCP reservation in your router so it never moves:</p>
        <pre class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-background p-4 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`ip -4 -o addr show scope global | awk '{print $2, $4}'   # e.g. eth0 192.168.1.50/24`}</code></pre>

        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground"><strong>6c. In your router's <span class="italic">Port Forwarding</span> section</strong>, forward all of these to that LAN IP:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 text-sm text-muted-foreground space-y-1">
          <li><code class="text-xs">44382/udp</code> → primary voice/video media (SRTP)</li>
          <li><code class="text-xs">44381/udp</code> <strong>and</strong> <code class="text-xs">44381/tcp</code> → fallback path for clients on UDP-hostile networks</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-xs text-muted-foreground">Do <strong>not</strong> forward <code class="text-xs">44380</code> (signalling) — it goes through the Cloudflare tunnel, not your router. Your public IP being dynamic is fine: signalling rides the tunnel, and LiveKit re-detects the public IP for media each time the container restarts.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="step-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-medium">Step 7: Validate Public Endpoints</h2>
        <pre class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-background p-4 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`curl -i https://auth.example.com/health
curl -i https://files.example.com/minio/health/live
curl -i https://connect.example.com/.well-known/letschat.json`}</code></pre>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Then make a test voice call between two clients. If they connect but no audio flows, the media ports from Step 6 are not reaching the host — recheck the forwards and the CGNAT test.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="step-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-medium">Step 8: Client Onboarding</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Users enter <code class="text-xs">https://connect.example.com</code> in startup and LetsChat will auto-discover backend URLs.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Discovery JSON example:</p>
        <pre class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-background p-4 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`{
  "spacetimedb": "wss://chat.example.com",
  "auth": "https://auth.example.com",
  "livekit": "wss://lk.example.com",
  "database": "letschat"
}`}</code></pre>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Signalling uses <code class="text-xs">wss://</code> because the <code class="text-xs">lk.example.com</code> tunnel ingress terminates TLS at Cloudflare. Media stays direct on the forwarded ports and is DTLS-SRTP encrypted independently.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="step-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-medium">Note: Voice behind CGNAT or a dynamic IP</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">If the CGNAT check in Step 6a showed <strong>different</strong> IPs, port forwarding cannot reach your host and voice will not work direct. The fix is a <strong>TURN relay</strong> that both sides reach outbound, so neither needs an inbound-reachable IP:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 text-sm text-muted-foreground space-y-1">
          <li><strong>TURN on a cheap public-IP VPS</strong> — relays media through a box with a stable, routable IP. Solves CGNAT and a dynamic home IP at once. All call media flows through it, so size its bandwidth accordingly.</li>
          <li><strong>Cloudflare Realtime (TURN)</strong> — managed relay at Cloudflare's edge; also hides your origin IP. Billed per GB of media.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-xs text-muted-foreground">A dynamic public IP on its own (no CGNAT) does not need TURN: signalling rides the tunnel, and LiveKit re-detects the public IP for media on each restart. Only an IP change <span class="italic">during</span> a session needs a LiveKit restart to recover.</p>
      </article>

    </section>

    <div class="flex items-center justify-between pt-4 border-t border-border text-sm">
      <a href="/self-hosting" class="text-muted-foreground hover:text-foreground transition-colors">← Back to overview</a>
      <a href="/self-hosting/caddy" class="text-muted-foreground hover:text-foreground transition-colors">Path B: Caddy →</a>
    </div>
  </main>
  <SiteFooter />
</Layout>

<style>
  .hero-glow {
    position: absolute;
    pointer-events: none;
    border-radius: 9999px;
    filter: blur(56px);
    opacity: 0.22;
  }

  .hero-glow-a {
    width: 360px;
    height: 260px;
    top: -80px;
    left: -80px;
    background: radial-gradient(circle at 40% 40%, color-mix(in oklch, var(--accent-blue) 80%, white 20%), transparent 70%);
    animation: drift 12s ease-in-out infinite;
  }

  .mini-pill {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    border-radius: 9999px;
    padding: 0.28rem 0.55rem;
    border: 1px solid oklch(1 0 0 / 0.16);
    font-size: 0.68rem;
    color: var(--color-muted-foreground);
    background: oklch(0.16 0 0 / 0.6);
  }

  .step-card {
    border: 1px solid oklch(1 0 0 / 0.12);
    background:
      linear-gradient(180deg, oklch(0.22 0 0 / 0.82), oklch(0.185 0 0 / 0.8)),
      linear-gradient(90deg, oklch(0.49 0.23 264.3 / 0.2) 0 4px, transparent 4px 100%);
    box-shadow: 0 14px 34px oklch(0 0 0 / 0.2);
  }

  @keyframes drift {
    0% { transform: translate3d(0, 0, 0) scale(1); }
    50% { transform: translate3d(8px, -12px, 0) scale(1.04); }
    100% { transform: translate3d(0, 0, 0) scale(1); }
  }
</style>

